"The sea belongs to us": Coastless Bolivia hopes that the court will open its way to the Pacific Ocean again
Seamen patroll a rigged headquarters for the fleet of La Paz.
Public buildings have a sea blue flag.
The bases of the fleet from Lake Titicacas to the Amazon bear the motto: "The sea belongs to us.
It is our duty to recover it.”
In coastless Bolivia, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict is still strong - and it is also the desire to again sail in the Pacific Ocean.
This hope is higher than for decades now when Bolivia awaits a decision by the International Court of Justice on the first October, after five years of consideration.
“Bolivia has the operation, a mood of unity and peace, and obviously awaits the result with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the international court’s decision on large screens across the country, in the hope that the Court of the Hague will judge in favour of Bolivia’s demands that Chile, after years of irregular discussions, must negotiate with Bolivia to allow them their own outlet to the sea.
The decision of Monday also has great importance for Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic native president who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he promised in late August.
However, some analysts believe it is unbelievable that the court judges Bolivia's advantage, and that not much would change even if it does.
The UN court, based in the Netherlands, has no right to assign Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible discussions.
The fact that the decision is announced only six months after the final arguments suggests that the case "wasn't complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And the last four years may have hurt rather than promoted Bolivia's chances.
"The question of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
She claims that Morales’ aggressive rhetoric has taken hold of Chile’s remaining goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will eventually continue the discussion, but it will be extremely difficult to do so after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, did not consider that the court's decision had been made unusually quickly.
Monday will give Bolivia "an outstanding opportunity to start a new era for the relationship with Chile" and a chance to "set a stop for 139 years of disagreements with mutual advantages," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, used the issue of the sea as a political crunch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to have access to the Pacific,” he said.
“The decision is a chance to realize that we have to move on from the past.”
