John Edward: Language skills crucial to global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools maintain outstanding academic results and this continued in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding test results, which are only strengthened by individual and collective progress in sport, art, music and other community engagements.
With up to 30,000 students in Scotland, the schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen careers and their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement customized curriculums, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and demanded topics in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we can not only rely on English when creating relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s test results show that languages are at the top of the list, with the highest number of approved results in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages received A in the final exam Higher Grade.
Data collected from SCIS 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students studying Mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages such as subject choices are now considered as important as natural knowledge, engineering, engineering and mathematics at curriculums in independent schools and beyond.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that employers for various reasons had difficulty filling their vacancies, with 17 percent attributed to a lack of skills in language.
That said, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs requiring language skills, these skills become necessary in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career choice, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries, automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 adults published by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent said they could not speak a foreign language well enough to keep a conversation in it, and where French was the only language that totaled a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
Therefore, it is so important to invest in language education for our children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance to find a meaningful job in the future.
In Scotland, each school will teach different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and get them with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future has at lut.
In a global economic environment, there is undoubtedly language that continues to be crucial for the country's future, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
