North Korea says they “never” will disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continuing sanctions deepened their distrust to the United States and it was not possible that the country would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “meaning measures to show its goodwill,” for example by stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the installations for nuclear tests and promising not to spread nuclear and nuclear technology.
“We don’t see a response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no chance that we unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to an approach divided into stages of nuclear power that would lead to North Korea's reward as it took progressive steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution entirely as Pyongyang previously did.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, where Kim promised to work against "decommissioning nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula" while Trump vowed guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has searched for a formal end to the Korean War 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first settle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also declined negotiations to relieve harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "decommissioning first" and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion and even object to the "declaration of ending the war," Ri says.
“The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a desirable dream for those people who lack knowledge of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leaders highlighted in the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party in this issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the Korean peninsula's nuclear disarmament would not have come to such a dead position."
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's future ability to reach the U.S. mainland with rockets was inevitable after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "raketman" on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "fully destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take measures for disarmament, but it said that much work remains and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for this and said that "if it takes two years, three years or five months," doesn't matter."
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the United Nations Security Council on Thursday that: “The maintenance of the security council’s sanctions must continue with force and without failing until we realize a complete, final, verified disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to stifle the funding of Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile program.
Pompeo met Ri during the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said that progress had been made. However, North Korea accused him a few hours later of setting "gangster-like claims".
North Korea promised a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile facility and even a nuclear crash complex if the United States took "corresponding measures".
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he sought were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore and moving towards normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take courses to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all doctoral students to improve their sleeping habits in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of studying through caffeine-filled "divings".
An academic study found that students at the world’s leading universities are often awkward when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he considers to be the first of his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deficiency on learning.
“At the end of that, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why don’t I know this until now, during my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organised for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of University Health Services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from serious sleep deficiency during the week.
The hourly course includes a range of interactive tasks.
In some of the course there is a picture of a student room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, coaches and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep deficiency can increase the risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change students’ behavior directly.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as one has the right to know about the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," Czeisler added.
“The culture of pride in “dyeing” still exists,” he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deficiency was a growing problem.
To ensure that you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain in starvation mode and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has read one of his courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course was an eye-opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study programme before starting their studies at the high-performance institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider putting an alarm for when to sleep and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can cause you to turn on the day, leading to insomnia problems.
