This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest fields for bats and other related species.
Fladdermus populations in Scotland and the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by building and development work that affects livelihoods and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials as well as attacks from huts.
Fladdermöss are not actually blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching the switch.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technology to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct investigations, examine bon and sometimes carry out rescue operations.
The organisation has also established Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserves at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
